Part B

Eurostat is the statistics office of the European Commission. It provides annual data on GDP per capita by country at current market prices in its tec00001 series. Scrape this data from the web into R using the method of your choice (its totally feasible, though a bit tricky, using rvest; there are alternatives).

Be sure that the GDP per capita variable does not include footnote flags or commas and both year and GDP per capita are numeric variables. Note: your observations are country-years. Be sure your result is in tidy format.

library(rvest)
## Loading required package: xml2
## 
## Attaching package: 'rvest'
## The following object is masked from 'package:purrr':
## 
##     pluck
## The following object is masked from 'package:readr':
## 
##     guess_encoding
library(countrycode)

gdp <- read_html("http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/tgm/refreshTableAction.do?tab=table&plugin=1&pcode=tec00001&language=en") 

countries <- gdp %>% 
    html_table() %>% 
    nth(5) %>% 
    pull(`EU (28 countries)`)

years <- gdp %>%
    html_table() %>% 
    nth(4) %>% 
    names()

gdp_rvest <- gdp %>% 
    html_table() %>% 
    last() %>% 
    as_tibble() %>% 
    rename_at(vars(str_c("X", 1:length(years))), ~ years) %>% 
    mutate(country_name = c("EU (28 countries)", countries)) %>% 
    filter(!str_detect(country_name, "EU|Euro")) %>% 
    gather(key = year, value = gdppc, -country_name) %>% 
    transmute(country = countrycode(country_name, 
                                    "country.name", "country.name"),
              year = as.numeric(year),
              gdppc = str_replace_all(gdppc, "\\D", "") %>% as.numeric()) %>% 
    arrange(country, year) %>% 
    filter(!is.na(gdppc))

gdp_eurostat <- eurostat::get_eurostat("tec00001", time_format = "num") %>% 
    filter(unit == "CP_EUR_HAB") %>% 
    transmute(country = countrycode(str_replace(geo, "UK", "GB") %>%
                                        str_replace("EL", "GR"),
                                    "iso2c", "country.name"),
           year = time,
           gdppc = values) %>% 
    filter(!is.na(country))

Part A

From your EB survey dataset, generate a working dataset that includes only the following variables for each respondent (R). Be sure to correctly identify any missing data and code it appropriately (i.e., as NA).

Variable Description
country_code Rs countrys two-letter ISO 3166 code (note: not ISO 3166-2)
country_name Rs countrys name (hint: use the countrycode package)
age_yrs Rs age in years, bottom-coded at 15, top-coded at 99
educ_9_17 Rs years of education, bottom-coded at 9, top-coded at 17
female2 Rs (binary) sex, coded 1 if female, 0 if male
married2 Rs marital status, coded 1 if currently married, 0 if not
children4 Rs number of children, top-coded at 4
rural2 Is Rs household in rural area or village? 1 if yes, 0 if no
employed2 Is R currently employed or self-employed? 1 if yes, 0 if no
poldisc2 When with friends, does R discuss political matters frequently? 1 if yes, 0 if no 
eb1 <- eb %>%
    transmute(country_code = str_replace(isocntry, "-\\w*", ""),
              country_name = countrycode(country_code, "iso2c", "country.name"),
              age_yrs = if_else(between(d11, 15, 99), d11, NA_real_),
              educ_9_17 = case_when(between(d8r1, 1, 9) ~ d8r1 + 8, 
                                  d8r1 == 10 & age_yrs - 5 <= 17 ~  age_yrs - 5,
                                  d8r1 == 10 & age_yrs - 5 > 17 ~ 17),
              female2 = if_else(between(d10, 1, 2), d10-1, NA_real_),
              married2 = case_when(d7r2 == 2 ~ 1,
                                   (d7r2 == 1 | between(d7r2, 3, 7)) ~ 0),
              children4 = if_else(d40b + d40c > 4, 4, as.numeric(d40b + d40c)), 
              rural2 = if_else(between(d25, 1, 3), as.numeric(d25==1), NA_real_),
              employed2 = as.numeric(d15a>=5),
              poldisc2 = as.numeric(qa2_1==1))

Model (Bonus)

Use lme4::glmer to estimate a two-level logistic regression model of whether EB respondents report frequently discussing politics with friends. Your model should include all of the other individual-level variables in your working dataset as controls, plus GDP per capita at the country level. For the purpose of this question, you may use rowwise deletion to deal with missing dataand variables that are completely missing should simply be excluded from the modeleven though IRL you would multiply impute. (Hint: use the argument family = binomial(link = "logit") with the glmer command to get a logistic regression model.)

library(lme4)
## Loading required package: Matrix
## 
## Attaching package: 'Matrix'
## The following object is masked from 'package:tidyr':
## 
##     expand
eb_data1 <- eb_data %>%
    mutate(gdppc_10k = gdppc/10000,
           age_10yrs = age_yrs/10)

m1 <- glmer(data = eb_data1,
            formula = poldisc2 ~ gdppc_10k +
                age_10yrs + 
                educ_9_17 +
                female2 +
                married2 +
                children4 +
                rural2 + 
                employed2 +
                (1|country),
            family=binomial(link="logit"))
